This utility recursively normalizes data structures by replacing all built-in Python container types with designated subclass nodes. It specifically checks for dict keys, list indices, and object attributes to ensure deep transformation throughout the structure.

```python
def normalize(ast: Node) -> Node:
    """
    Normalize an AST nodes.

    all builtins containers are replace by referencable subclasses
    """
    res = ast
    typemap = {DictNode, ListNode, TupleNode}
    if type(ast) is dict:
        res = DictNode(ast)
    elif type(ast) is list:
        res = ListNode(ast)
    elif type(ast) is tuple:
        res = TupleNode(ast)
    # in-depth change
    if hasattr(res, 'items'):
        for k, v in res.items():
            res[k] = normalize(v)
    elif hasattr(res, '__getitem__'):
        for idx, v in zip(range(len(res)), res):
            res[idx] = normalize(v)
    if type(res) not in typemap and hasattr(res, '__dict__'):
        subattr = vars(res)
        for k, v in subattr.items():
            setattr(res, k, normalize(v))
    return res
```

The function successfully standardizes the structural representation of AST objects. Keep in mind that this relies heavily on the node classes implementing proper attribute handling for the recursive traversal to work effectively.
